Genetic diversity of a highly imperiled, habitat specialist, Etheostoma marmorpinnum, from Little River, TN

Jacob F. Brumley and Rebecca E. Blanton
Johansen Lab of Ichthyology at Austin Peay State University, Department of Biology and Center of Excellence for Field Biology

Figure 1. Etheostoma marmorpinnum from Little River at River Johns

Abstract

The federally endangered Marbled Darter, Etheostoma marmorpinnum, is endemic to the Little River in eastern Tennessee. Anthropogenic land use in the upper Tennessee Valley has contributed to degradation and fragmentation of E. marmorpinnum habitat. These changes have resulted in a decrease in population abundance and occurrence of the species, reducing its range from one that historically included the South Fork Holston River to a 20 rkm stretch of the lower Little River. E. marmorpinnum is patchily distributed across this reach of the Little River, utilizing a specific habitat of low-flowing pools with clean gravel and cobble substrate, bracketed by Fort Loudon Dam downstream and Perrys Mill Dam upstream. Our objectives were to estimate genetic diversity at site and species levels to provide a baseline for conservation actions and for future genetic monitoring. Fifty-six individuals were captured and clipped while snorkeling at 3 known localities that spanned the range of the species. Twenty variable microsatellite loci were used to collect genotypic data for all individuals, and a standard suit of population genetic analyses were performed.

Introduction (Short Version)

Habitat loss and fragmentation cause declines in population connectivity and abundance, increasing genetic drift and influencing genetic diversity. Decreases in abundance and genetic diversity within a population lead to inbreeding and genetic homogenization of the population, reducing the fitness of both the individuals and the population as a whole. Imperiled species that are already in threat of extirpation or extinction may not survive a reduction in fitness. The federally endangered Marbled Darter, Etheostoma marmorpinnum (Blanton & Jenkins, 2008), is found in the Little River of Tennessee. Its restricted range and patchy habitat, small population size, and limited larval dispersal have made the species highly suseptible to major changes in their available habitat. Although once known in the South Fork Houlston River, the darter is only found in a 20 rkm stretch of the lower Little River and is restricted in all directions by dams (Fort Loudoun Dam, TN R.; Cherokee Dam, Houlston R.; Douglas Dam, French Broad R.; Perrys Mill Dam, Little R.). Although protected under the ESA of 1973, the threat on the Marbled Darter is needed to be monitored. Genetic monitoring can be used by USFWS to determined future directions for the conservation of this species.

Objectives

  1. Estimate genetic diversity at site and species levels

  2. Provide genetic baseline for future conservation and genetic monitoring

Methods

Study Area: Etheostoma marmorpinnums range is restricted to a 20 rkm stretch of the lower Little River in eastern Tennessee. This stretch is bracketed by Fort Loudoun Dam downstream on the Tennessee River and Perrys Mill Dam upstream on the Little River. Three sites were selected, being the only known thriving populations (TN-33 Bridge Crossing, River Johns, and Coulters Bridge).

Methods: Tissue samples were taken from the upper lobe of the caudal fin of 56 individuals. DNA was extracted from all tissue samples, using a Qiagen DNeasy Blood and Tissue Kit. The extracted DNA was amplified through PCR for 20 previously published microsatellite primers for Etheostoma lemniscatum. R was used to run a standard suit of population genetic analyses for genotypic data.

Results

Genotypic data was analyzed using various packages in R. Each package used measured given populaiton genetic metrics that determine genetic diversity. The following packages were used in this study:

PopGenReport gives a complete report of population genetic metrics. From this report, we can look specifically at Allelic Richness, Private Alleles, Null Alleles, Mean Alleles per Locus, Deviations from Hardy-Weinberg Equillibrium, Genetic Fixation (FST), and Heterozygosity.
